{"key":"post-8513760","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8513760</id>\n<content>It probably didn't come close to pasteurization temps.&amp;nbsp; You want to insert a meat thermometer into the center of your substrate, and begin timing one hour from the time the thermometer reaches 140F.&amp;nbsp; It will probably take an hour to reach that temp, and you'll need the stove on.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;For small amounts, I use quart jars, because the water can surround the jars, so they heat up faster, and it also doesn't screw up your moisture content.&amp;nbsp; You can get a feel for how by watching this video clip:&amp;nbsp; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.iplayerhd.com/player/6ae8b820-1e39-49d1-8cf0-3ffa27380804.aspx&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;www.iplayerhd.com/player/6ae8b82&lt;wbr&gt;0-1e39-49d1-8cf0-3ffa27380804.asp&lt;wbr&gt;x&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8513793</next>\n<prev>8513744</prev>\n<first>8513654</first>\n<last>8514012</last>\n<when>1213251727</when>\n<utime>06/12/08 09:22 AM</utime>\n</post>"}